Title: Money Doctors 
Author-Name: NICOLA GENNAIOLI  
Author-Name: ANDREI SHLEIFER  
Author-Name: ROBERT VISHNY  
Abstract:
  type="main"> <title type="main">ABSTRACT</title> <p>We present a new
 model of investors delegating portfolio management to professionals based
 on trust. Trust in the manager reduces an investor's perception of the
 riskiness of a given investment, and allows managers to charge fees. Money
 managers compete for investor funds by setting fees, but because of trust,
 fees do not fall to costs. In equilibrium, fees are higher for assets with
 higher expected return, managers on average underperform the market net of
 fees, but investors nevertheless prefer to hire managers to investing on
 their own. When investors hold biased expectations, trust causes managers
 to pander to investor beliefs.
Journal: Journal of Finance 
