Title: Inflation Risk in Corporate Bonds 
Author-Name: JOHNNY KANG  
Author-Name: CAROLIN E. PFLUEGER  
Abstract:
  type="main"> <title type="main">ABSTRACT</title> <p>We argue that
 corporate bond yields reflect fears of debt deflation. When debt is
 nominal, unexpectedly low inflation increases real liabilities and default
 risk. In a real business cycle model with optimal but infrequent capital
 structure choice, more uncertain or procyclical inflation leads to
 quantitatively important increases in corporate log yields in excess of
 default-free log yields. A panel of credit spread indexes from six
 developed countries shows that credit spreads rise by 14 basis points if
 inflation volatility or the inflation-stock correlation increases by one
 standard deviation.
Journal: Journal of Finance 
